# python weird tuple iterable upacking


+python +tuple +iter +iterable +unpack


Here is the weird syntax for tuple (or any iterable in fact) unpacking in
Python that apparently works like a charm.

```python
[[value]] = ([1_000], )
# value == 1_000
[[*foo, bar]] = (range(10),)
# foo = [0, 1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6, 7, 8]
# bar = 9
```

The number of square braces is equivalent to the number of nested iterables.
The example above gives two, but can be any, and it works with most (all?)
tuple unpacking idioms.

The double-square-bracket on the left hand side is doing (double)
assignment-unpacking to get the single value back out of these two nested
sequences
